820b6d4b-2985-5adb-ae2a-8e1ef419193c,tg:rubgr:610,e73_Descriptions,,id.desc,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,"[recto] Death of Virgin.The chiaroscuro effect, unsual for Bruegel and only partly to be found in his grisailles (Resurrection, Adulteress and partly in Wise & Foolish Virgins) comes from the graphic arts. N. Hogenberg, Death of Margaret, the direct prototype for, is only one of the examples typical of this artist, there are e.g. other 4 Evangelists etchings after Frans Crabbe (Hollstein, V, Crabbe, Nos. 38-41 (p. 86, see also [Arthur E.] Popham, [= Engravings and Etchings of Frans Crabbe van Espleghem”], The Print Collector's Quarterly, 22, 3, [1935], pp. 202 & 203) of which the Evangelist St. Mark is signed NH and only this one of the whole set is listed by Hollstein (IX, p. 60) under N. Hogenberg, N°19. Cf. also the engraving by Crabbe (signed with cray-fish) of Christ on Mount of Olives (Hollstein, V, Crabbe, N° 11). Both Crabbe and N. Hogenberg were Malines artists as well as Frans Verbeeck (Schüler Crabbes?) and Bruegel's mother -in- law who was born at Malines; [verso] Death of Virgin. [Heinrich] Th. Musper, Die Holzschnitte des Nicolas Hogenberg aus München, Jb.pr. Ksl. [= Jahrbuch der Preußischen Kunstsammlungen], LXIII, 1942, pp. 171-179, citaten pp. 178-179.",descriptive note,Nederlands,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,

column4: <content>[recto] Death of Virgin.The chiaroscuro effect, unsual for Bruegel and only partly to be found in his grisailles (Resurrection, Adulteress and partly in Wise & Foolish Virgins) comes from the graphic arts. N. Hogenberg, Death of Margaret, the direct prototype for, is only one of the examples typical of this artist, there are e.g. other 4 Evangelists etchings after Frans Crabbe (Hollstein, V, Crabbe, Nos. 38-41 (p. 86, see also [Arthur E.] Popham, [= Engravings and Etchings of Frans Crabbe van Espleghem”], The Print Collector's Quarterly, 22, 3, [1935], pp. 202 & 203) of which the Evangelist St. Mark is signed NH and only this one of the whole set is listed by Hollstein (IX, p. 60) under N. Hogenberg, N°19. Cf. also the engraving by Crabbe (signed with cray-fish) of Christ on Mount of Olives (Hollstein, V, Crabbe, N° 11). Both Crabbe and N. Hogenberg were Malines artists as well as Frans Verbeeck (Schüler Crabbes?) and Bruegel's mother -in- law who was born at Malines; [verso] Death of Virgin. [Heinrich] Th. Musper, Die Holzschnitte des Nicolas Hogenberg aus München, Jb.pr. Ksl. [= Jahrbuch der Preußischen Kunstsammlungen], LXIII, 1942, pp. 171-179, citaten pp. 178-179.</content>
<object.title>Christ and the Woman Taken in Adultery</object.title>
